<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-736-387  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 736 387.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Dec 17 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japan: formal research into virus protection.andO;(Information-technology Promotion Agency)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Takahashi, Ken.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Research and DevelopmentGovernment AgencyComputer virusesJapan. Information-Technology Promotion Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>JAPAN: FORMAL RESEARCH INTO VIRUS PREVENTION 12/17/90 TOKYO, JAPAN, 1990 DEC17 (NB) -- The Information-technology Promotion Agency or IPA, the affiliateof Japan's Ministry of International Trade and Industry, has started researchinto the development of applications to fight computer viruses.andP;  The researchis significant in that the new software would be effective against all kindsof computer viruses, even new ones, whereas existing vaccine programs arenot.andM;As a first step, the agency is examining encryption software based onidentification information.andP;  Although the research is currently on a basicstage, the agency is planning to promote the software by making a pilot modelby next year.andM;Also, the agency is doing research into AI (artificial intelligence) vaccinesoftware, which would learn new types of viruses and resist them.andP;  The agencyintends to make available the result of the research to software houses toreduce the attacks of computer viruses.andM;(Ken Takahashi/19901213)</TEXT></DOC>